http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Shantou is a hub in four international cable networks, all built since the late 1990s. From your point of arrival on Longhu Beach, this state-of-the-art China Telecom facility could be mistaken for one of the many resort hotels that line the waterfront. Yet the new technology and luxury tourism of Shantou lies only twenty miles from Guiyu, a town that has been called “the electronic-waste capital of the globe.” Every year, the city receives over 1.5 million pounds of discarded computers and other electronics, most of it from overseas. Tens of thousands of laborers strip cables and dismantle circuit boards to extract valuable metals, but the toxic byproducts of these machines have devastated the workers’ health and surrounding environment.

A futuristic cable station sits next to the expansive wetlands of the Dongtan national wildlife sanctuary. Signals arrive through major underwater networks, while swans, cranes, spoonbills, shorebirds, and many species of fish stop here along their migratory routes. Like the landing station, Chongming Island’s salt-water marshes and tidal flats are transitional zones that mediate between land and sea. Although it feels rural, the island is only twenty miles from central Shanghai and is connected by a freeway. Visitors fill the tree-lined boardwalks that crisscross the reserve, observing the local fauna. Meanwhile, data is surveilled as it passes through the station: a white sign with red text marks the presence of underground cables and bears the name “PLA Unit 61398,” a group believed to engage in electronic monitoring and cyber-attacks against the U.S..

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: This tag specifies that the associated page is a cable.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Across history, there have been three kinds of cable technology: copper telegraph cables, coaxial telephone cables, and fiber-optic internet cables. To create a page for a new cable, see the reference page for cables.

Completed in 2000, the consortium-owned China-U.S. Cable Network was the first direct cable route between the two countries. It consists of dual Pacific crossings, forming a ring structure with connections along the west coast of the U.S. and between several Southeast Asian hubs. Only a year after it entered service, however, the anchor of a fishing boat off Chongming Island disrupted much of the traffic between China and the U.S..

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: You make your way through sludge and silt to come ashore – quite a different experience from the clear seawater of the southern Japanese islands. A Spanish and then Dutch colony in the seventeenth century, Tanshui (also known as Dansheui) grew to become the largest port in Taiwan by the late 1800s. Coal and tea were exported in vast quantities from the natural harbor where the Tanshui (or Tamsui) River meets the Strait of Taiwan. In 1887, an underwater telegraph cable joined the bustling city to Fuzhou on the Chinese mainland, and a year later the Taipei Telegraph Academy opened nearby. But in the early twentieth century, the buildup of silt at the river mouth caused much of the shipping traffic to move east to Keelung. While its port status dwindled, Tanshui retained its position as an international cable hub. Several fiber-optic systems arrived in the early 2000s, linking the town to points throughout East Asia and the Pacific. Twin landing stations, owned by competing telecom carriers, are situated along a quiet beach west of the city, famous for vivid sunsets and a popular leisure destination for residents of Taipei.

You find yourself in a dark, small stone building, held by a Japanese military man. Outside, things are quiet. A road lined with palm trees leads into the dark green mountains, overlooking shallow blue-green harbors. Boats are prohibited from anchoring here because of the cable. Midway between Taiwan and the main island of Okinawa, Ishigaki has recently become essential for Japanese international and military communications. In 1897, this building has been newly built to transmit telegraph signals to Okinawa and Taiwan. In years to come, the quiet will be shattered by wars. The building will become busy with transmissions, bombed, and damaged, although not destroyed. Long after it is abandoned, some locals will sense that ghosts remain inside.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Okinawa Prefecture encompasses a string of small islands, about 300 miles south of the rest of Japan and only 200 miles northeast of Taiwan. Geographically and politically separated from the other Japanese islands, the Okinawan islands remained more or less self-governing until the Meiji Restoration, when they became a target for Japan's expansionist aims. After winning the Sino-Japanese War in 1895, Japan immediately began laying cables connecting its territories, including one between Okinawa and the other prefectures. More importantly, in 1897, a cable was laid that connected Okinawa Island to Taiwan, allowing international telegraph communications to and from Japan and its colonial holdings. For this endeavor, Japan even built its own cable ship, the Okinawa Maru. Not long afterward, during the Russo-Japanese War, the Japanese used the ship to cut the telegraph cable connecting Yap and Shanghai. They then retrieved the cable and connected Yap to Okinawa instead.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Long before it was a cable hub, Katong was a center of private wealth in British Malaya. Colonial elites established giant mansions, coconut plantations, and weekend villas along the waterfront in this East Singapore district beginning in the early nineteenth century. Though some of these structures have been preserved and restored, often painted bright colors, the still-affluent neighborhood has also seen some major physical transformations. The beach where you emerge from the APCN-2 network didn’t even exist before the 1970s. It was created as part of a massive land-reclamation project designed to add more space for housing on the island. Modern apartment towers and Singapore’s largest park now occupy the expanded coastal area. Soon after the artificial beach was completed, a telephone cable arrived from Hong Kong, followed by connections to regional fiber-optic networks in the 1990s and early 2000s.

The Deep Water Bay cable station is situated on one of the most expensive properties in our undersea network. Overlooking a small bay on Hong Kong’s south shore, the station was built when there was little development in the area. Today, it is the oldest still operational station on the island and has been the connection point for numerous cables since the 1960s. In the intervening years, Hong Kong’s affluent residents migrated to the nearby hills and the area’s forest was replaced with mansions. Unlike the typical windowless structures that populate the cable system, Deep Water Bay’s postwar architecture offers a lookout onto the beaches and ocean below. Peering out of the station windows, you have a better view of the bay than Hong Kong’s richest man. There are few people here to enjoy it, however: since it opened, machines have replaced many of the workers.

Waves crash up against a thick seawall that spans the coast of Toucheng. Much of the shore here in northeast Taiwan is comprised of sand rock, eroded by ocean waves and monsoon winds. Spectacular surface formations are cut into the sedimentary rock, some locals observe that these even resemble tofu. Yet the erosion here is not entirely natural. The presence of manmade structures on 56% of Taiwan’s coast, this seawall included, has sped up the disappearance of the coast. These structures interrupt the flow of sand, causing it to accumulate on one side and to quickly erode on the other. The nearby Toucheng beach, which once stretched for two kilometers, is now severely diminished, and the coast has retreated up to 100 meters inland. This seawall keeps the shoreline intact for both waves and cable stations, but provides an additional challenge for cable laying. Companies have to bore a hole through the thick walls in order to thread their networks through.
In 1921, the Japanese Government laid a cable from Nagasaki, its cable hub closest to Asia, to Dairen.

Dairen, Manchuria is today’s Dalian, China. This port city sits on a peninsula that juts out into the Yellow Sea, bisecting the Chinese mainland and North Korea, and threading together the region’s histories of communications and transport. At the time of its first cable landing, this piece of land was under Russian control. Valued in part because of its southern location, the port gave the Russians year-round access to the Pacific. During their occupation, the Russians gradually transformed Dairen from a small fishing village to a busy naval and shipping harbor, where small wooden warehouses, cranes, and a railroad lined the water. When the Russo-Japanese War broke out in 1904, the Japanese quickly took control of the port and brought in a telegraph cable. In 1908, a new cable linked the city to China, but accepted messages only in Japanese outside certain portions of the day. Eventually the city was transferred back to the Russians, and finally to the Chinese government in 1950.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Like many port cities in Asia, Nagasaki was “discovered” by imperial powers – in this case, the Portuguese – and developed for trade. In the nineteenth century, Nagasaki became a busy transit point, with a vibrant ship-building industry, an anchorage site for the Japanese navy, and a telegraph cable landing point. Three years after its first submarine telegraph cable was landed in 1871, the telegraph company established a headquarters here, in a large two-story office building abutting the harbor. Within a few years, Japan would build up its internal landlines, and the country would be connected to the rest of the world via Nagasaki. The importance of this station was clear to Japan and its enemies. Described as “clutching the aeortic artery of international communications in Japan,” Nagasaki, as a hub and military harbor, was also a target. The cable to Vladivostok was taken out of service during the Russo-Japanese War, but the city remained undamaged. During World War II, however, Nagasaki was hit with the atomic bomb, the second and last to ever be deployed, killing several hundred thousand people. After the Japanese surrender, the city would slowly rebuild. Old communications lines were taken out of service, and new coaxial cables laid in their place.

The optical cable system was commissioned in 2000 by an international consortium of nearly 100 corporate investors.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Muntok is a young city by Indonesian standards – it was founded in 1732 by an order of the Sultan Palembang Darussalam, and at that time consisted of only seven wooden houses. When the cable landed in 1859, Muntok was still a small town, now comprised of red-roofed houses clustered around a bay. Tall, straight palm trees lined the empty dirt roads. The engineer who installed the cable wrote of Muntok: “All serene. Great trouble with the telegraphists … who sleep on duty, and otherwise keep Siemens constantly in the station.” The little village woke up over the following decades as the Dutch built houses and canals, using the town as a communications node and a site for exporting indigenous goods. Then, as now, the area was rich in tin, and the harvesting, smelting and exporting of the ore put Muntok on the map for colonial trade. The cables have gone, however, and it remains a quiet smelting and mining spot, an offshoot to the larger and more central Palembang.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Palembang is not on a coast, but about 40 miles inland from the South China Sea, in the south-east corner of Sumatra. But the city has been an important trading and maritime center for millennia due to its location on the Musi River. This wide, grey river runs through the town, dividing the city into halves, and, during the colonial period, easily receiving large military and merchant ships. On one bank, a walled city was built by the Dutch, while the opposite bank remained lined with smaller traditional wooden houses on stilts with deep red roofs. The Musi River both divided and connected – it made it easier for the Dutch East Indies Company to open a trading post here in 1619, and by the 18th century, over 50,000 pounds of spices were exported from the city every year. The telegraph cable, brought in 1859, was used in part to transmit information about this trade. The last section of cable had to be laid using proas, local vessels which snaked 60 miles of cable up the narrow and deep river to its widening at the shores of Palembang.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Famous for its fortifications more than its receptiveness, Taku has been a critical gateway to China since the 1500s. It is just downriver from the busy trading city of Tianjin, where the Hai connects to the Yellow and Yangtze rivers, and boats filled with goods have traveled for centuries. The water that connects Taku also made it vulnerable. To protect against Japanese pirates, the Chinese erected forts here in the 16th century. During the Opium Wars of the 19th century, these forts were expanded in response to concerns about Western imperial invasion. The concerns were valid: in 1858 the British won a battle here which opened the port to foreigners, allowing foreign legations, Christian missionaries, and the legal import of opium. The site remained highly contested for the rest of the century. In 1900, the Chinese government commissioned both the Great Northern Telegraph Company and the Eastern Extension Telegraph Company to lay cables to Taku. Things were tense: signals were often intercepted, foreign boats lurked in the harbor, Chinese troops filled the forts, and almost 2400 Russian soldiers were stationed in Tianjin. In June of that year, as the Boxer Rebellion erupted in Beijing, the occupying western nations collaboratively and successfully attacked the Taku Forts in a violent battle, leaving the area awash in “rivers of blood.” As was the case in many locales, cables followed conflict, and a month later, a German company began the construction on its own telegraph to Taku.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Tschifu is today called Yantai, meaning “smoky tower.” In a way, this harbor town was always a critical communications node: the name refers back to the Ming Dynasty, when locals would light smoky fires to warn the village of approaching Japanese pirates. On the north-eastern tip of the Shandong Peninsula, Tschifu was directly south of Dairen, due west of Seoul, and straight north from Shanghai. Its central location made it an ideal cable hub during the telegraph era. In the first decade of the twentieth century, ten cables were landed here, connecting to Tsingtau, Port Arthur, Taku, Dairen, Shanghai, and Wei-hai-wei. Even before the cables were landed, the city had long been an important traffic hub: it had been an international trading port for almost half a century and seventeen nations had established embassies there.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Danish Great Northern Telegraph Company was a key player in the early telegraph network. The company was able to fund a system connecting parts of Europe and Asia in part due to the desire of Russia and other nations to have a secure communications route that ran independently of British links.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Tseung Kwan O, known in English as “Junk Bay” for the many fishing boats that once dotted its waters, is now a booming tech center. As is true for much of urban Hong Kong, this area is built upon reclaimed land and the nearby Tseung Kwan O Industrial Estate extends over fill that used to be the bay. The Industrial Estate, one of many set up by the Hong Kong Science & Technology Parks Corporation, is the headquarters of Hong Kong's largest television broadcaster. It also houses the content of a significant slice of the Hong Kong internet:  twelve major data centers are located here, including those of HSBC, the Japanese firm NTT Communications, and Telehouse Hong Kong. Signals transit in and out of the data centers to destinations around the world via the four submarine cables that land here. Behind the Industrial Estate, however, in the enormous South East New Territories landfill, the debris of such accelerated flows remain.

EAC-C2C represents the merger of the EAC (East Asia Crossing) and C2C (City-to-City) cable networks, completed in 2007 by Pacnet. Together, they form Asia’s largest privately owned cable system with a total of seventeen landing sites across Japan, Korea, China, Taiwan, Hong Kong, the Philippines, and Singapore.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Constructed in 2008 by a consortium of six telecom companies, the Trans-Pacific Express (TPE) cable is a major link between sites in the South China Sea (China, South Korea, and Taiwan) and the west coast of the United States. An extension to Japan opened in 2010. It greatly increased connection speeds across the Pacific, bringing them up to those found in trans-Atlantic cables.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Banyuwangi means "Fragrant Water" in Javanese. Landing on its shores in the late nineteenth century, you emerge from vibrant blue waves. A gateway between Asia and Australia, this Dutch colony is a key stopping point for telegraph cables. In 1871 a link to Darwin was landed here, connecting Australia to the rest of the world through Java’s shores. While more a century in the future, surfers will travel from around the world to ride Banyuwangi’s waves, nineteenth-century cablemen complain that its waters were “uninviting” because of the “ever-present danger of crocodiles and sharks.” Here the cable intersects both turbulent waters and an ancient spiritual history. From the sixteenth to eighteenth century, the city was the capital of the Hindi Kingdom of Blambangan, which controlled the eastern tip of Java before it was taken over by the Dutch. To dig a trench for the telegraph cable to Singapore, native convicts were employed as laborers. But when they unearthed a Hindu Temple from 700 AD, the laborers refused to continue and women, who reportedly were unaffected by the native “superstitions,” had to be called in to complete the job.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: “Imagine yourself in a black room, with most of the light and air cut off by screens, and blinds, a mirror lamp burning close to you, and a temperature of about 95 in the shade,” recounts one cable worker of his time in Darwin. Conditions were rough for the early operators at Australia’s first undersea telegraph station, which hooked the continent into the colonial network in 1871. In the summer the temperature was often over 100 degrees Fahrenheit, even despite the Hindu and Aboriginal servants employed to “waft away the heat.” The quarters of the telegraph men frequently flooded and stores often ran out of rations. When the cable was first landed, the men’s quarters had not even built, and for two years they lived in tents. During this time the terrestrial cable, linking Darwin to Adelaide, went out frequently, cut by Aborigines across the continent. Even despite the hardships, the cablemen were still a privileged lot in this colonial outpost. Their rooms, once built, were “lofty,” and their station was eventually furnished with amenities like a piano and billard table. “Perhaps the the greatest luxury they can boast of,” one reported, “is plenty of water gratis, for which others have to pay ninepence per bucket.”

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Was located at 44 Northam Road, now Jalan Sultan Ahmad Shah.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In George Town at the turn of the 19th century you witness the beginnings of a modern city. The streets are lined with warehouses and ghauts, wide steps leading from the street to the water. Banks, trading areas, and emporium stores are beginning to appear along Beach Street. Since its founding by the British East India Company in 1786, the town has grown into a bustling trading port and commercial center. George Town has been built on water: its commercial center stands on a swampy wetland that was leveled and filled in the early 1800s. Seeing that this was precarious, English settlers built their bungalows high up on top of Penang Hill, forbidding natives to do the same. The settlers’ wealthy Chinese business partners were allowed to build in the middle part of the hill. The cable – part of the emerging modern city – surfaces close to the water, but ultimately connected those who lived far above it.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCi.value: Bill Glover, “Cable Timeline: 1845-1900,” History of the Atlantic Cable & Undersea Communications: from the first submarine cable of 1850 to the worldwide fiber optic network, accessed June 22, 2013, http://atlantic-cable.com/Cables/CableTimeLine/index1850.htm.
Visions of Penang Archives Online (My Heritage My Penang), accessed June 22, 2013, http://www.visionsofpenang.com.my

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Malacca was an ancient fishing village before it was taken over by the Portuguese in the 1500s, followed by the Dutch and the British. When first telegraph cable arrived in 1879, the port city had both native and colonial populations, and each responded differently to the new technology. According to the British news report from Malacca, the local Malays avoided the cable house after dark, “even now when they see [that] no demon is concealed in the coil of wire.” For Malacca’s European inhabitants, however, the telegraph link was more mundane than mysterious. “One would have thought,” the article laments, “that the laying of the cable would have brought us more into communication with Singapore . . . that the wants of our little Settlement and more news about us would have appeared in the Journals but such is not the case.” Although the settlers did not feel fully connected, the cable had at least one practical benefit: “we get the time more exact than we used to.”

A trading post since the second century, the island of Singapore was a hub of exchange for Southeast Asia long before the British settled there in 1819. When the first underwater telegraph cable arrived forty years later, Singapore was a bustling port city, what one nineteenth-century cable survey called “that thriving halfway house between Europe and the East.” Although produced in a factory in London more than six thousand miles away, the Singapore-Muntok cable was insulated with the coagulated sap of trees native to the region. The Malays had used this substance, known as gutta-percha, for generations to make whips and other products. In the 1840s, a Scottish doctor stationed in Singapore took notice of the sap and brought it back to London. Gutta-percha made an ideal electrical insulator and became the material of choice in the cable industry.  By the time gutta-percha-encased wires populated Singapore's waters, demand had all but wiped out the local flora that made its transmissions possible.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Batam cable station looks out across rusty brown sand and a dark blue sea. Somewhere across that water is Singapore, where the other end of the cable has landed since 2006. The station shares the shore with many other industries – nearby you glimpse silhouettes of cranes and oil rigs. Not much farther along the coast there are ship-repair yards and a number of ferry ports. Fiber-optic signals run underneath, and support, the transfer of goods and people to and from Singapore on the water's surface. Part of a free trade zone, the whole area is a bit lassiez-faire. Batam does not exert a large amount of control over the information, commerce, or people that stream in and out. The city itself serves the appetites of the workers and businessmen who have come to build up these industries, offering restaurants, bars, and an infamous nightlife. Even the taxis and the driving speeds remain unregulated.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Appropriately named Keoje, Korean for “great crossing,” this island is the landing site of several international submarine cable networks, though it is still smaller than the hub in nearby Pusan. As you come ashore through clear waters, the sound you hear is not heavy rainfall but the pebbles on Hakdong beach tumbling in the surf. Named after a crane (“hak” in Korean), this wing-shaped beach sits in a valley covered by flowering camellia plants, sheltered from the industrial shipyards and granite mines further north. Eschewing the discrete architecture of many contemporary cable facilities, the Korea Telecom landing station calls attention to itself with an ornate design. Decorative columns and topiaries line the station’s brick and glass entryway, which faces away from Hakdong’s beachfront promenade.

The system is specially routed to avoid areas prone to seismic activity while providing additional capacity along the region’s existing international networks.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: When it was finished in December 2005, the consortium-owned Southeast Asia-Middle East-Western Europe 4 cable provided both additional bandwidth and greater redundancy along the bulk of the previous-generation SeaMeWe-3 line between the Mediterranean and Singapore. SeaMeWe-3, however, extends significantly further to points in China, Japan, Australia, the U.K., and Germany, among others.

Sri Racha is an industrial economic center in the province of Chonburi, about an hour’s drive from Bangkok on an eight-lane freeway. Rice, sugar, rubber, tapioca, coconut, and seafood are all produced in vast quantities before being exported from Laem Chabang, the largest container port in Thailand and one of the busiest commercial harbors in the world. Shipping lines dovetail with the paths of underwater cables that link Sri Racha to other communication hubs in Southeast Asia and across the Pacific. Most of the district’s beaches are muddy and rocky, with development often reaching the water’s edge. But cables land on one of the few slivers of sand in the area north of Laem Chabang before making their way inland past factories and manufacturing plants to the state-owned cable station.

Although undersea fiber optic cables were introduced in the region in the 1980s, the TVH cable, completed in 1996, was the first system to link Thailand, Vietnam, and Hong Kong with a communications channel equivalent to 80,000 simultaneous phone calls.
The Hawai'i-2 cable was a short link that connected the HAW-1 cable that landed at Hanauma Bay to the transpacific link that came ashore at Makaha. Laid in 1964, it held only 128 telephone circuits.

In the 1950s, the first transpacific telephone cable was landed at Hanauma Bay, solidifying Hawai‘i’s as a hub of Pacific communications. The station was buried underground like many Cold War-era infrastructures, disguised as part of the hillside to prevent it from attack. The burying of the station was not its only impact on the environment: installers had to dynamite their way through a reef to ensure the cable had a safe path out to sea. More than fifty years later, this path has become a corridor of environmental tourism. The hole in the reef, now dubbed the “Telephone Cable Channel,” draws scuba divers and snorkelers through one of Hawai‘i’s foremost nature preserves. The cable, once used to traffic telephone calls, has been re-purposed by marine scientists to monitor the undersea environment, sensing aquatic lifeforms and seismic movements of the ocean floor.

Heading inland to the Makaha cable station, you surface in a parking lot, in a manhole barely visible under the dirt. Along the beaches to the south of this town reside hundreds of houseless people. O‘ahu’s west shore is home to one of the state’s largest native communities and largest homeless population. In Makaha alone, 32% of its residents live in poverty. Yet, the west shore is also a transit point for a large percentage of the state’s international signal traffic. Since the 1960s, almost all of the island’s coaxial and fiber-optic cables have terminated at three cable stations along this short 30-kilometer stretch. The seemingly divergent histories of telecommunications success and economic deprivation in the area are intertwined, linked to the area's long-standing military occupation. Weapons testing sites and military installations, such as the Lualualei Naval Reservation and the Schofield Barracks, displaced residents from the west shore’s inland valleys. At the same time, the U.S. military was once one of the biggest customers of the cable networks, giving them both an economic boost and a layer of protection when they were set up during the Cold War.

AT&T has been integral to the laying of submarine cables since the 1950s. During the Cold War period, cable laying was "club" affair - only nationally-affiliated telecommunications companies could participate. AT&T facilitated all of the United States' transoceanic projects during this time, and built an number of cable stations on US shores.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: When China began to struggle against imperialism in the late 1800s, Qingdao was an important node of resistance. The Boxers, an anti-imperialist, proto-nationalist Chinese movement, had a strong presence in area, and in 1897, the Chinese government began building up a military base here to protect against foreign invasion. Shortly thereafter, German troops seized and occupied this fort. After a year of fighting, China conceded the area to Germany, who re-named the city Tsingtau, a French transliteration of the original name. This small Chinese fishing village was transformed into a German administrative and economic center, with tall three-story stone buildings, wide streets, electricity, and a navy base. At the turn of the century, two telegraph cables were landed, one connecting to Tschifu and one to Shanghai. Today, two major cable systems continue to land at Qingdao, linking the city to Korea and across the sea to California.

The portion of the network owned by TM is branded Cahaya Malaysia (“cahaya” is the Indonesian word for “light”).

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Built in the 1970s, Nanhui station was the first landing site for international coaxial cables in China. Early signals surfaced on the muddy shores of Nanhui district, then mostly farmland, roughly thirty miles southeast of central Shanghai. Now the area is almost unrecognizable, transformed by rapid industrialization that has displaced many of its former inhabitants. Large-scale development projects have even altered the local geography, continuing a process begun millennia ago when Nanhui was formed by silt deposited at the mouth of the Yangtze River. New cables pass by a huge artificial island that contains the recently constructed Shanghai deep-water container port, linked to the mainland by a twenty-mile bridge. And just east of the station, an entire city for 800,000 is being built from scratch on land reclaimed from Hangzhou Bay.

Entering service in 1997, the FLAG (Fiber-Optic Link Around the Globe) Europe-Asia cable system connects the United Kingdom with Japan via more than a dozen landing sites. The cable, now operated by an Indian telecom, was the subject of a 1996 Wired magazine article by cyberpunk author Neal Stephenson in which he traveled to “six countries and four continents trying to get a grip on this longest, fastest, mother of all wires.”

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Before it was cleared for industrial development in the 1970s, Tuas was a small but active fishing village on the western tip of Singapore. Local fishermen would lay palm fronds on the water’s surface above a submerged net, attracting fish with the shade. The name “Tuas” derives from the Malay word for hauling up the net and the catch it contains. Although this technique is rarely practiced anymore, modern-day Tuas pulls together large-scale networks of various kinds. Global cable systems arrived starting in the late 1990s, connecting to the red and white SingTel station, adorned with a series of porthole-shaped windows and a tall, latticework communications tower. A power plant feeds Singapore’s grid with roughly a fifth of its total supply. Near-constant marine traffic flows through the naval base, shipyards, and container port, while waste is transferred to an offshore landfill. And roadways converge at a checkpoint and mile-long bridge that links Tuas to Johor, Malaysia, offering one of the only terrestrial paths off the island.

For roughly two decades beginning in the late 1970s, this small village in the northwest Philippines was linked to the urban centers of Singapore, Hong Kong, and Okinawa. By 1980, Currimao was considered one of the largest and most advanced cable hubs in the world. But when the Asia-America Gateway system was being built in the early 2000s, the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company selected a landing site more than a hundred miles south in the province of La Union, closer to Metro Manila. As quickly as it appeared, Currimao faded from the network map. Today it is perhaps best known for a series of coral rock formations, shaped by the ocean into dramatic caverns and spires over thousands of years.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Although it started out as a small farm town, Shanghai grew into an important and busy port during the Qing Dynasty. In 1842, after the British defeated the Chinese in the first Opium War, Shanghai became a treaty port, occupied by British forces and open for international trade. Throughout the end of the 19th and beginning of the 20th centuries, the city grew rapidly. Tall municipal buildings and three-story stone houses with red roofs lined the wide and busy streets. The ports were congested with naval and trade ships from Britain, France, and Japan. The first telegraph cable arrived in 1871, connecting the city to Singapore and Hong Kong. As the cable was laid up the Yangtze River to Shanghai, men armed with rifles patrolled it to stop sailors from throwing anchor and severing the connection. By 1916, ten more cables - sponsored by a range of governments and militaries - had landed here, linking to Japan, Russia, Yap, the Philippines, and other Chinese ports.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: You can journey to the village of Maruyama along cables from the U.S., Australia, or various sites in Southeast Asia. But upon reaching the station, you may feel as if you’ve traveled even farther—and back in time. Across the road is Rosemary Park, a detailed replica of a sixteenth-century English town. Built in 1997 by British architects, the tourist attraction includes a working windmill, formal gardens, a duck pond, and a recreation of Shakespeare’s childhood home, complete with lifelike statues and time-specific furnishings. Shakespeare referenced rosemary in his plays, and Maruyama is known for producing this and other herbs. While the park looks to the past, the modern cable station is one of Japan’s most popular landing sites. Both enact a kind of virtual transit to far-off locales.

The Asia Submarine-cable Express cable surfaces two miles outside the city of Daet in the small coastal village of Bagasbas, popular for its kite-surfing and other aquatic sports. From the broad, sandy beach, you move up an elevated promenade that protects the village from storm surges during typhoons. To the left is an aging airport runway, repurposed in between flights as a jogging and cycling path. Turning right, you reach the modern landing station, owned by the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company. When it was connected in 2012, the cable was framed as a benefit for both international exchange (it offers the most direct communication route to Japan) and the local economy. After touring the station with a group of Japanese officials, Daet’s mayor praised its attractiveness to companies that wished to develop call centers, one of the fastest-growing industries in the Philippines.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Tourists step on a long cable conduit without looking twice, intent on getting to the ruins of an Japanese antiaircraft gun constructed during World War II at the far end of Gun Beach. Guam held strategic military value in part due to its position as a cable hub. At the other end of the beach is the Hotel Nikko, one of the early Japanese five star hotels in the area, a structure dependent on the island’s advanced communications  infrastructure. Undersea cables, shuttling signals to the United States, Australia, and Japan, bisect a material remnant of the Japanese wartime attack and one of the largest indications of Japanese development on the island, two sites with which undersea cables are intertwined. The cable conduits themselves are worn down and blend in with the rocks on the beach. In the water their surfaces are smooth, but rippled, like the ocean. In them, you can see traces of the atmospheric and geological currents that have long positioned the island as central to transpacific movement. Tumon Bay is a node in the cable network, a point of interconnection and redistribution, not simply of electronic signals, but of cultural and political currents.

Kitakyushu has been a networked industrial center in southern Japan for more than a century. Beginning in the early 1900s, Japan’s largest steel mill refined iron ore from Korea and China into metal for shipbuilding and the rapidly expanding railroad system. This made Kitakyushu a target during the Second World War, including the original target for the bomb later dropped on Nagasaki. Today, the city is home to Kyushu’s largest ferry port and second-largest train station, as well as a factory that produces more than three thousand miles of submarine cable each year. It’s also the birthplace of celebrated Japanese crime novelist Seichō Matsumoto. In his 1957 bestseller Points and Lines, police investigators discover two bodies on a secluded beach and use railway schedules to locate the suspects in time and space.

To build GOKI, AT&T commissioned two Japanese cable companies to pull up 800 miles of retired underwater networks, including portions of TPC-5. These fragments were then reengineered and combined with new fibers to create a much faster optical link between Japan and Guam.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The consortium-owned Southeast Asia Japan Cable (SJC) runs from Singapore to Japan, with branch connections to Thailand, Brunei, the Philippines, Hong Kong, and China. Intense demand along the communication route prompted capacity upgrades less than a year after it was built in 2013.

A 12th-century sea wall lines the edge of a small village where cables land. Locals come here to take in the panorama, looking east across the ocean. The clear seawater carries you up to white, rocky beaches, abutted by deep green brush leading into steep hills and low forests. The history of this village stretches back hundreds of years, when the sea wall and castle were built, forming the administrative and cultural center of the area. Yet the remoteness of the village made it appealing to cable companies during the coaxial period. After the destruction of World War II, companies surfaced cables far away from urban centers, like Okinawa City, which might be potential targets. In the 1970s and 1980s, a number of important international cables were landed here in Gushikami, making this rural land a submarine communications hub. More recently, the abandoned TPC-2 cable to Guam was revived for geophysical observations rather than telephone calls.

Sasebo became an essential node for military communications at the turn of the twentieth century. This Japanese port is about 100 miles south of the southern tip of Korea, across the ocean from Shanghai. The town had been a small fishing village until the Meiji Period, when it quickly became an important naval base because of its protected, nearly land-locked, deep harbor. In 1898, a major railway station was opened here, anticipating the other traffic to come. Cables came in from Port Arthur, and out across the East China Sea to Dairen and Tsingtau. The town grew up around the transiting traffic, becoming a busy port and a wireless station. Like many other hubs in the Pacific, its connectivity would become a liability in future years. The wireless station here is believed to have broadcasted the message to attack Pearl Harbor during World War II. Four years later, Sasebo suffered severe bombing by allied forces, and was on the list of potential targets for the dropping of the atom bomb.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The cable lands on Back Beach, a strip of towering upscale hotels, small seafood restaurants, and military installations left over from the American War. It winds under an enormous temporary infrastructure of beach chairs and food carts that support weekenders from Saigon, past the bunker-like buildings that fortress the beach, and inland to the VTI cable station in the center of Vung Tau, identifiable by its huge radio tower. Behind the cable station, a statue of a woman holding a cell phone brings the site good luck. For many years, indeed, Vung Tau has been lucky: since the United States military landed their first undersea telephone on Back Beach, all of the subsequent cables have chosen this spot, from the TVH cable in 1993 to the TGN Intra-Asia cable in 2009. Yet the latest link, the Asia-America Gateway cable, has not been so fortunate. Since its initiation it has been cut several times, severely affecting internet traffic in Vietnam.

Asia-America Gateway (AAG), opened in 2009, was the first high-bandwidth optical cable to provide a direct link between Southeast Asia and California (via the Philippines, Guam, and Hawaii). Positioned further south than other trans-Pacific routes, AAG avoids the seismically active areas near Taiwan where earthquakes are known to cause cable disruptions.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Surfacing at Whitford Beach, you are careful not to be hit by one of the sixteen-foot tall waves also making its way to the shore. This beach is beautiful and active: the hollow and powerful waves draw surfers from throughout the area and the soft sands bring visitors to lounge, fly kites, and ride horses along this sunny stretch of land. Several major international cables have also landed here, connecting Australia to Asia. About ten miles inland is the Perth International Telecommunications Centre (PITC), which occupies 710 square acres of flat, dry land in a rural suburb. Since 1986, the center has handled much of Australia's signal traffic. With its own power plant, and a 15-meter diameter antenna for communicating with spacecrafts, PITC is a stark contrast to the brick house on the shores of Cottesloe that welcomed the trans-Indian-Ocean telegraph cable in 1901.
